</p>
<div class="mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id="Analogues_in_higher_dimensions">Analogues in higher dimensions</h2><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Sierpi%C5%84ski_triangle&amp;action=edit&amp;section=11" title="Edit section: Analogues in higher dimensions"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class="mw-default-size" typeof="mw:File/Thumb"><a href="/wiki/File:Rendering_von_Seite_Sierpi%C5%84ski-Pyramide_20230513_002_RGB16.png" class="mw-file-description"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/63/Rendering_von_Seite_Sierpi%C5%84ski-Pyramide_20230513_002_RGB16.png/250px-Rendering_von_Seite_Sierpi%C5%84ski-Pyramide_20230513_002_RGB16.png" decoding="async" width="250" height="250" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/63/Rendering_von_Seite_Sierpi%C5%84ski-Pyramide_20230513_002_RGB16.png/500px-Rendering_von_Seite_Sierpi%C5%84ski-Pyramide_20230513_002_RGB16.png 2x" data-file-width="10000" data-file-height="10000" /></a><figcaption>Sierpiński pyramid recursion (8 steps)</figcaption></figure>
<p>The <b>Sierpiński tetrahedron</b> or <b>tetrix</b> is the three-dimensional analogue of the Sierpiński triangle, formed by repeatedly shrinking a regular <a href="/wiki/Tetrahedron" title="Tetrahedron">tetrahedron</a> to one half its original height, putting together four copies of this tetrahedron with corners touching, and then repeating the process.
</p><p>The Sierpiński tetrahedron can also be formed by starting with a single tetrahedron, removing octahedra from it or recursively combining quadruples of tetrahedra into larger tetrahedra.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-18" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-18"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>18<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup>
